<br>
But I (54th monk) was along on a raid into Trak's lair.  First pull attempt I was just chain tagger for a 59 monk.  I know he hadn't seen this guide, I don't know if he had ever pulled Trak before.  While Trak was in his safe little corner, he proceeded to run up the left side stairs/path and throw a hammer at a jug or prot.  Which succeeded in pulling the Trak, the juggs and prot.  Needless to say, that turned into a near total wipeout.  Some people camped/lived and the raid was reborn within an hour.  Note, even though the rest of the raid was tucked back into the tunnel well, all the nasties managed to sniff them out and decide to visit.<br>
<br>
After CR that monk had to leave for RL reasons.  So it was passed on to me to pull the lair.  This was my only my second time in Seb, but I figured I'd give it a shot. I had read the guide, and figured I had at least a 50/50 shot at pulling it off.<br>
<br>
Trak was no longer at his safe point, so we recruited a pally, grouped him with the CoH mage, and sent him on his way.  A timing misunderstanding by the mage meant the pally was dead before the CoH completed casting.  Trak was moved however, mission completed, so we got the Pally to Seb, summonsed, rezzed and we continued on.<br>
<br>
I move up to the feign spot, hit the deck and proceed to wait.  The only thing I don't like about this spot... is that the Prot blocks my view of the nearby wandering jugg, making impossible to determine if the jugg is in position 2 or 3.  Soon I see my chance, and off I go to make my first pull.  But silly me, I float too far over the edge and sink before I get to the Prot and have to reset.  No biggie.<br>
<br>
So here is where I make my critical mistake.  I'm still waiting for the right set up to pull, but the Prot is blocking my view.  I'm not sure how close I can get to the static juggs/frog before aggroing them, so instead of trying to inch closer for a cleared viewing angle, I try another tactic.  I have an eye of zomm device and figure I'll try that for a better view.  Except that as soon as I click it, the casting effect (has to be) triggers cascading aggro through the lair.  Trak, Juggs, Prot etc.  Needless to say I FD right there and see if things will settle down so I can /q and try again.  Except that the train rolls right on by me and proceeds to massacre the raid crew in the tunnel.  I get up and head back down to help/die in a more convienent location at this point.  At this point, the classes that lived or camped, or had to leave for RL reason left us with insufficent numbers to perform a CR on the spot, and necro summons/rez's were done at the zone later.<br>
<br>
I believe that even casting that close to the mobs in Trak's lair was aggro inducing, because to the best of my knowledge, Eye of Zomm is no longer aggro inducing.  What I'd like to know, is what caused the aggro to get passed all the way back to the raid force in the tunnel?  Shouldn't I have been able to die as a sacrifice and then continue on after rez?  Anyone else  have any other input?  How close to the statics can you get before FDing (to get a better view angle of the wanders)?  And in response to GukMonster's post, are Javelins an exception to the &quot;Don't hit anything rule&quot; because of their extreme range?<br>
<br>
Another tips for the puller: Don't be group leader, if you were a leader and get asked to pull, reform your group.  Makes it easier to change group formation if you need a CoH mage suddenly, and allows you to /q and get back into the group with more ease.<br>
<br>
